From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] net: ps4_mts v88 - stop 1000BT advertise + RGMII delay + MT7531 DSP defaults

v87 added Orbis's "unconditional tail" of mts_mac_init.  If v87 hardware
test still leaves link DOWN with partner's Remote Fault (reg 5 bit 13)
stuck high, this v88 patch tries the next-most-likely fix per the
4-agent v87+v88 dig.

Key insight from deepseek's v88 fallback research: Orbis was written
for Realtek RTL8211 PHYs, so its MMD 0x1e/0x1f writes are all
Realtek-specific.  Mainline mt7531_phy_config_init (drivers/net/phy/
mediatek/mtk-ge.c) does MT7531-specific DSP register writes that Orbis
NEVER does.  On real MT7531 silicon coming out of reset, these DSP
parameters are at POR (power-on reset) defaults that may be insufficient
for reliable 1000BT signal training.  Result: partner sees malformed
signal -> asserts Remote Fault -> AN never resolves to a working link.

This patch adds three changes at end of mts_mac_init (after the v87
tail writes):

1. Stop advertising 1000BT (reg 9 & ~0x0300):
   Partner reg 5 = 0xc5e1 doesn't include 1000BT.  Our advertising it
   triggers 1000BT master/slave training that our PHY can't complete
   (since we lack the DSP setup), partner sees bad signal, RF asserts.
   Forcing 10/100-only removes 1000BT from the training path.

2. RGMII delay (MMD 0x1e regs 0x13/0x14 = 0x04):
   Mainline mtk-ge.c sets these for proper RGMII TX/RX skew.  Orbis
   doesn't.  MT7531 default may be 0 (no delay), causing signal timing
   errors at the MAC<->PHY interface.

3. MT7531 DSP defaults (deepseek's primary finding):
   - Near-echo offset: MMD 0x1e reg 0xa6, bits 15-8 = 0x3
     OR-set 0x0300 into the high byte; keep low byte
   - 100M MSE threshold: MMD 0x1e reg 0x123 = 0xffff
     (both lo and hi thresholds to 0xff)

Deferred to v89 if v88 isn't enough: SlvDPSready time write via
token-ring protocol (TR ch=1 node=0xf data=0x17 bits 22-15 = 0x5e).
Token-ring needs MediaTek's vendor C22 page 0x52b5 access pattern
(regs 0x10/0x11/0x12) which is more complex.

Pass criteria:

  - dmesg shows "v88: 1000BT_CTRL (reg9) 0x???? -> 0x????"
  - "v88: RGMII delay set: TX=0x???? RX=0x????"
  - "v88: near-echo offset MMD0x1e r0xa6: 0x???? -> 0x????"
  - "v88: 100M MSE threshold MMD0x1e r0x123 = 0xffff" (readback)
  - phy_ctrl: LP ABILITY shows RF=0 (partner clears Remote Fault)
  - linkreg transitions from 0x00000b18 to 0x00000???? with bit 0 set
  - 100M full duplex link (since partner advertises 100/10 only)

If link still down with this patch:
  - v89: add SlvDPSready TR write
  - v90: force 100M full duplex without AN (BMCR = 0x2100)
  - v91: try a different PHY init - skip Orbis writes entirely,
         apply only mainline mt7531_phy_config_init
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -505,6 +505,70 @@
 		       bar + MTS_LINK_STATUS);
 		(void)readl(bar + MTS_LINK_STATUS);
 
+		/*
+		 * v88: stop advertising 1000BT.  Per deepseek-v41's v87 dig,
+		 * partner reg 5 = 0xc5e1 has bit 13 (Remote Fault) set.  Partner
+		 * advertises only 10/100, not 1000BT.  Our advertising 1000BT
+		 * (reg 9 bit 9) may trigger 1000BT master/slave training that
+		 * our PHY can't complete (since Orbis Realtek MMD trim writes
+		 * are no-ops on MT7531), causing partner to see bad signal and
+		 * assert RF.  Force 10/100-only by clearing reg 9 entirely.
+		 *
+		 * If v88 makes partner clear RF + link comes up at 100M full:
+		 * the 1000BT training path was the blocker.
+		 */
+		if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x09, &v16) == 0) {
+			mts_smi_c22_write(mts, 0x09, v16 & ~0x0300);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v88: 1000BT_CTRL (reg9) 0x%04x -> 0x%04x (stopped advertising 1000BT)\n",
+				 v16, v16 & ~0x0300);
+		}
+
+		/*
+		 * v88 RGMII delay per mainline mtk-ge.c.  MMD 0x1e regs 0x13/0x14
+		 * control PHY-side RGMII delay.  Orbis doesn't set them (relies
+		 * on Realtek silicon defaults).  On MT7531 with reset state,
+		 * defaults may be wrong.  Mainline value: 0x04.
+		 */
+		mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0x13, 0x04);
+		mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0x14, 0x04);
+		{
+			u16 td = 0, rd = 0;
+			mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0x13, &td);
+			mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0x14, &rd);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v88: RGMII delay set: TX(MMD0x1e r0x13)=0x%04x RX(r0x14)=0x%04x\n",
+				 td, rd);
+		}
+
+		/*
+		 * v88 MT7531 DSP defaults (from deepseek's v88 dig of
+		 * mainline mt7531_phy_config_init).  Orbis NEVER does these
+		 * because Orbis was written for Realtek - MT7531 silicon
+		 * defaults at POR are insufficient for 1000BT signal training,
+		 * causing partner to see malformed signal and assert RF.
+		 *
+		 *   - Near-echo offset: MMD 0x1e reg 0xa6, bits 15-8 = 0x3
+		 *   - 100M MSE threshold: MMD 0x1e reg 0x123 = 0xffff
+		 *     (both lo/hi thresholds to 0xff)
+		 *
+		 * Skipped for v88: SlvDPSready time (TR ch=1 node=0xf data=0x17
+		 * bits 22-15 = 0x5e) - token-ring protocol access, defer to v89
+		 * if v88 isn't enough.
+		 */
+		if (mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0xa6, &v16) == 0) {
+			u16 nw = (v16 & 0x00ff) | 0x0300;
+			mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0xa6, nw);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v88: near-echo offset MMD0x1e r0xa6: 0x%04x -> 0x%04x\n",
+				 v16, nw);
+		}
+		mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0x123, 0xffff);
+		if (mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0x123, &v16) == 0)
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v88: 100M MSE threshold MMD0x1e r0x123 = 0x%04x\n",
+				 v16);
+
 		/* Final AN restart per Orbis (BMCR |= 0x1200). */
 		if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x00, &v16) == 0) {
 			mts_smi_c22_write(mts, 0x00, v16 | 0x1200);
